<bioghist altrender="history" encodinganalog="545" id="a2">
<head>History</head>
<p>The <corpname>Belding Brothers and Company</corpname> were silk manufacturers in <geogname>Rockville, CT</geogname>, with additional mills in <geogname>Northampton, MA</geogname>, <geogname>Belding, MI</geogname>, <geogname>San Francisco, CA</geogname>, and <geogname>Montreal, Canada</geogname>; the brothers had extensive business interests.</p>
</bioghist>
<scopecontent encodinganalog="520" id="a3">
<head>Scope and Content</head>
<p>The eight folders in the collection contain correspondence from <persname>A.N. Belding</persname> and from <persname>M.M. Belding</persname> to <persname>W. P. Hetherington</persname>, their agent in <geogname>Belding, MI</geogname>. The letters date 1893, 1896, 1899-1903. The correspondence indicates the range of the <corpname>Belding Brothers and Company</corpname> interests including: <corpname>Belding Building Loan Association</corpname>, <corpname>Belding Land Improvement Company</corpname>, <corpname>Hotel Belding</corpname>, <corpname>Citizens Electric Light Company</corpname>, and other business concerns. The letters show the Belding brothers' relations with the city, their interest in city politics, as well as mill employee relations and Belding's discriminatory property leasing practices.</p>
</scopecontent>

